!TITLE
YOU CAN'T HAVE TOO MANY KIDS
!WORDS
 »Where previous generations considered marriage without children 
unthinkable, ours makes the childless state, if not a positive good, 
at least a worthwhile alternative.«

 This writer, who grew up in a family of seven children, finds it 
amazing that people consider her current family large. She has three 
children.

   She has discovered that having a lot of children, i.e. more than 
one or two, is considered absolutely antisocial and environmentally 
irresponsible.  Living in India, she has seen "overpopulation" 
first-hand and believes that the real problem is not the huge, hungry 
families of the poor but the small families of higher-class consumers 
who consider cars, TVs, air- conditioning, and plastic bags as basic 
necessities of life. People who are really serious about cleaning up 
the environment should focus on eliminating the things that are 
ruining the earth--not children.

   The writer admits that child-rearing, like any great undertaking, 
involves a good deal of upheaval, but argues that the goal is worth 
it. In the past, choosing to not have children was unthinkable.  Our 
generation views childlessness as a viable option, if not a positive 
good. However, she feels that the fact that most people do want 
children (albeit only one or two) indicates that our society does not 
want to be anti- children.  Yet in today's world it is increasingly 
easy to tuck one child or two into the parents' lives right along 
with careers, house payments, and adult activities.  A family of 
half-a-dozen or so kids is different.  There's always someone who 
needs something (a nose wiped, a story read, a shoe tied), and the 
parents' needs come last.  Such parental selflessness, which was just 
part of life in the past, seems out of step with contemporary 
psychology ( "You've got to take care of yourself ") but quite 
consistent with the Gospel ( "Whosoever shall lose his life shall 
preserve it ").

   In the final analysis, having lots of children is a matter of 
trust.  Do we have the faith the accept the gifts God sends without 
worrying about our own inadequacies?  Not everyone is capable of 
being a good father or mother to many children, "but those who can 
deserve our admiration and encouragement."

      "You can't have too many kids" by Jo McGowan.  U.S. Catholic, 
Mar 1991.  Pages 34-36.
!TOPICS
CHILDREN
FAMILIES, LARGE
PARENTING
OVERPOPULATION
SELFISHNESS, PARENTAL
ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS
CHILDLESSNESS
TRUST IN GOD
MCGOWAN, JO
US CATHOLIC, 9103 PP34-36
