!TITLE
WHEN GOD WAS A WOMAN
!WORDS
 »Whether they are reviving a vanished faith or inventing a new one, 
it is the gender of the deity that counts.«

 Many Earth Day celebrations this year had religious (but not 
Christian) overtones.  Across the U.S. a number of goddess- 
worshipers naturally got involved in the ecological celebrations 
since the deity they worship is often depicted as Gaia or Mother 
Earth.  The goddess movement has been growing rapidly in this 
country, with some insiders claiming there are over 100,000 women 
involved.  For these women, the Judeo-Christian God is too 
patriarchal, and they insist that the goddess is not just a female 
God.  Rather than being transcendent like the God of the Bible, she 
is thought of as being present in every person and in everything in 
nature.

   Her followers are involved in an eclectic variety of witchcraft, 
paganism, New Age concepts, and radical feminism. Proponents of 
goddess worship say that the movement is anything but new. They claim 
to be reviving an ancient religion that was wiped out by patriarchal 
religions around 4,000 B.C.  Two recently published scholarly books 
use archaeological evidence to support this theory.  Critics argue 
that the facts the feminist writers present are contradictory.  One 
thing is clear, however, they consider the gender of the deity they 
worship more important than the historical roots of the current 
movement.

      "When God was a woman" by Richard Ostling. Time, May 6, 1991. 
Page 73.
!TOPICS
FALSE RELIGIONS
