!TITLE
THE PLIGHT OF U.S. CHILDREN
!WORDS
 »The raw numbers describing the plight of American children are 
alarming.«

   A day in the life of the children of the United States:
   One drops out of school every eight seconds of the school day.
   One is abused every 47 seconds.
   One is arrested for a narcotics violation every seven minutes.
   One is killed or wounded by a gunshot every 36 minutes.
   The popular perception is that children who are in poverty live in 
minority neighborhoods in the inner city and are growing up in 
non-working single-parent families.  Statistics from the Children's 
Defense Fund, however, indicate that the majority of poor children 
are white and do not live in the city.  Almost 50% of these children 
belong to families that are NOT on welfare. Single-parent families do 
account for a significant proportion of those living in poverty, but 
even if they are omitted from a comparison of the U.S. to other 
countries, it is clear that we have one of the highest child poverty 
rates among industrialized nations.

      "The social costs of an empty lunchbox" by Carey Burkett. 
Sojourners, Aug/Sep 1991.  Pages 4- 5.
!TOPICS
CHILDREN
POVERTY, CHILDREN IN
WELFARE FAMILIES
SINGLE-PARENT FAMILIES
STATISTICS, CHILDREN
BURKETT, CAREY
SOJOURNERS, 9108- PP4-5
