!TITLE
HOME EDUCATION INCREASINGLY POPULAR
!WORDS
 »We are very concerned that many parents who think they are 
qualified to teach their youngsters simply are not. Society 
ultimately has to pay for any mistakes --National School Boards 
Assoc.«

   According to a recent Associated Press release, research conducted 
for the U.S. Department of Education shows that between 250,000 and 
360,000 children are were taught at home by their parents rather than 
sent to schools during the 1990-91 school year.  Some proponents of 
home education put the figure at 500,000 or more.  In any case, there 
has been a dramatic increase in the last few years.  As recently as 
the late 1970s, only around 10,000 children were being home-educated.
   Some teachers' organizations say that it is a very dangerous 
trend.  The executive director of the National School Boards 
Association calls it "a giant step backward into the 17th century."  
He expresses concern that many parents are just not qualified to 
teach their children and his organization has lobbied along with the 
National Education Association for legal restrictions on home 
schooling.  According to Michael Farris of the National Center for 
Home Education, the opponents of home education have not been very 
successful.  In legislative battles in ten different states so far 
this year, home schooling has won out every time.

   Home school families think they are winning in other ways as 
well.  One nationwide survey of home schoolers reveals that they 
ranked at the 80th percentile or better on standardized achievement 
tests.  Other studies have shown that these children tend to be 
well-adjusted socially and emotionally and have leadership potential.

      "Home education increasingly popular" by Mary Esch.  World, Jun 
29, 1991.  Page 12.
!TOPICS
HOME EDUCATION
SCHOOLS, PUBLIC
EDUCATION, HOME
TEACHERS' ORGANIZATIONS
