!TITLE
RELIGIOUS SELF-HELP LITERATURE
!WORDS
 »Since there is little substance in their books-- little in the way 
of information, arguments, or new ideas--their power of persuasion is 
purely personal.«

   When Americans speak of religious freedom, they typically mean the 
right to worship as you please rather than the right not to worship 
at all.  In fact, it is practically un-American to not believe in 
God.  Most popular religious literature reflects this intolerance of 
unbelief in its attitude toward nonbelievers, sometimes condemning 
them, sometimes pitying them. Such books, especially those of the 
self-help variety, mix the sacred and the secular, attempting to use 
psychological language and techniques to instruct, inspire, or 
indoctrinate.

   Authors like M. Scott Peck, James Dobson, Charles Swindoll, Gordon 
MacDonald, and David Seamands don't argue or reason with readers; 
they smugly announce the truth, without distinguishing fact from 
opinion.  Admittedly, thousands of people are helped by their books.  
The persuasiveness of the writers, however, is strictly in their 
personal appeal since the books themselves lack substance, offering 
very little in terms of new ideas or information.

   The following are some familiar common themes that emerged from a 
sampling of over 30 popular Christian books:  The world is basically 
a moral ordered place.  Dependence upon God is essential. 
Individualism is both sinful and unhealthy.  To have low self-esteem 
insults God.  Evil is a type of personality disorder.  All that is 
required for salvation is faith.

   With their mixture of pop psychology and religion, these messages, 
though aimed at the conservative Christian subculture, are obviously 
influenced by prevalent mainstream ideas about goodness, health, and 
social relations.  The religious writers rationalize their use of 
psychology by saying that it has finally seen the light regarding 
some eternal truths.  At the same time, they also devise ways to make 
the insights of psychology more acceptable to their audience, e.g., 
equating illness with sin.

   All these writers advocate submission to God as the ultimate 
authority but overlook the recent historical evidence that 
enslavement to evil is much more likely to be associated with 
submissiveness than with independent thinking. Yet they tenaciously 
cling to the doctrine of original sin and criticize psychoanalysis 
for not holding individuals responsible for their own behavior.

   Criticizing Swindoll's emphasis on grace, the writer claims that 
he teaches there is no punishment for bad deeds and no reward for 
good ones.  Not only is Swindoll down on religious pluralism and 
intellectualism, he discourages readers from thinking for 
themselves.  So when he laments that fact that people don't read much 
anymore, he's like a porn dealer bemoaning the decline in morality.  
She implies that non- Christian women will be offended by Swindoll's 
advocacy of traditional sex roles and accuses him of anti-Semitism 
for suggesting that the holocaust was a consequence of the Jews' 
rejection of God. She ridicules MacDonald's penchant for organization 
and careful use of time and seems to feel his insights on dealing 
with sin are simplistic.  She upbraids Dobson for being critical of 
feminism and for advocating corporal punishment and "unabashed 
authoritarianism."

   Most popular religious books fail to provide a model for moral 
behavior in the world and thus offer no basis for community.  They 
makes list of legalistic prohibitions--abortion, atheism, and 
homosexuality--but do little to help people resolve ethical dilemmas.

      "Saving therapy: exploring the religious self-help literature" 
by Wendy Kaminer.  Theology Today, Oct 1991.  Pages 310-325.
!TOPICS
