!TITLE
GIVING AN INGROWN CHURCH AN OUTWARD FOCUS
!WORDS
A pastor discusses how to turn a church from an inward focus to 
looking out to the community and its needs.  His suggestions 
included: 1) Bring people face to face with the needs.  One pastor 
(without prior notice) asked the congregation one Sunday morning to 
board chartered buses.  They drove through trailer parks, sprawling 
new subdivisions, apartment complexes, stately old neighborhoods and 
student housing. Tour guides and a prepared script helped the members 
get a glimpse of the outside world. 2) Highlight ministry, not 
managers.  Too often we take our most committed people and make them 
rear-echelon bureaucrats instead of front-line officers.  3) Give 
everyone permission to minister. All programs and ideas don't have to 
come from the pastor.  The author has only four guidelines a ministry 
must meet: A. Don't ask for money.  B. You, not my staff, must run 
the ministry. C. Stay out of morally questionable areas.  D. Stay out 
of doctrinal disputes.  4) Don't train people too soon. It's best to 
train people who have already gotten involved.  5) Emphasize 
flexibility over buildings.  6) Be patient.  "Stay close to the Head 
and wait for him to release the body in ministry."

     "Giving an ingrown church an outward focus" by Frank Tillapaugh. 
Leadership, Summer 1988. Pages 22-27.
!TOPICS
EVANGELISM
VISION
MINISTRY, COMMUNITY IMPACT
TILLAPAUGH, FRANK
LEADERSHIP, 88-SUM PP22-27
