!TITLE
THE SEARCH FOR THE GOOD SHEPHERD
!WORDS
Christians' perceptions of leadership have been so dominated by the 
personality cult of our age that we often do not use appropriate 
criteria to differentiate between good leaders and bad.  The 
Christian community has bought into a secular model of leadership, 
simply covering it over with a thin layer of orthodoxy.  This 
tendency of clergy and lay people alike to employ an unscriptural 
ideal of leadership can result in either pastor burnout or what might 
be called "congregation abuse." Both shepherd and flock are 
responsible to act out of a Biblical understanding of leadership.

    Four essential principles are: 1) Vision is a gift of God, not a 
by-product of personal dynamism. Having vision is what distiguishes a 
leader from a mere manager.  2) A leader's self- confidence must be 
rooted in prayer and humility. Prayer is essential because it puts 
the individual in right relationship with God and with others. 3) 
Sincere, practical love--not charisma--is the basis for Christlike 
leadership.  Love is what sets the true leaders apart from a 
commander. This kind of love is not a sentimental emotionalism but an 
act of the will and it must characterize all of a leader's 
relationships.  4) Failure is a God-given opportunity.  Failure is 
where redemption starts, and the greatest test of Christian 
leadership is the ability to be honest about failures.

    Scriptural leadership rests of the paradox of strength growing 
out of weakness (2 Cor. 12:9-10).

      "The search for the good shepherd" by John Haggai. Ministries 
Today, May/Jun 1990.  Pages 80-83.
!TOPICS
LEADERSHIP
PASTORS
FAILURE
VISION
