!TITLE
CHARISMATICS AND APARTHEID
!WORDS
A charismatic revival continues to sweep across South Africa. 
Hundreds of charismatic churches have been started since 1979 and are 
bridging the racial gap better than other groups seem to be able to. 
Along with the political change that has begun, observers detect a 
process of cultural change in which charismatics are in the 
forefront. Through these churches blacks and whites both are being 
shown a new vision of the lordship of Christ.  Research has shown 
that South African charismatics are surprisingly open and sincerely 
desire to bring apartheid to an end.

    About 5 to 10% of whites in South Africa belong to independent 
charismatic churches.  If traditional Pentecostals and black 
independent churches are included, it may be that 35% of the nation's 
people are involved in charismatic churches. These churches attract 
20 to 60% blacks, reflecting a level of integration found in no other 
organization.  When 130 people in these churches were surveyed about 
the South African law that keeps people living in separate areas 
based on skin color, all but three said that it was sinful.

      "Charismatics and apartheid" by Irving Hexham and Karla 
Poewe-Hexham.  Charisma & Christian Life, May 1990.  Pages 62- 70.
!TOPICS
SOUTH AFRICA, CHRISTIANS IN
CHARISMATICS
