!TITLE
WINGING IT: WHAT CATHOLICS THINK ABOUT HEAVEN
!WORDS
The majority of Americans (77%), according to a Gallup poll, believe 
in heaven and three out of four of those believers think they have a 
good to excellent chance of going there.  However, their ideas of 
what heaven will be like are less certain.  Only half of the 
respondents thought heaven meant being in the presence of God and 
less then half expect to be reunited with loved ones there.  Among 
Catholics two views predominate. One view is that heaven cannot be 
known and any specific image we hold is theologically unsupportable.  
The other perspective is that the idea of heaven is a distraction 
keeping us from doing God's work in the here and now.  A more 
educated laity that is questioning the authority of the Church is 
less inclined the accept the official teachings about heaven.
      "Winging it: what Catholics think about heaven" by Brian Doyle. 
U.S. Catholic, June 1990. Pages 6-13.
!TOPICS
HEAVEN
THEOLOGY
CATHOLICS
LIFE AFTER DEATH
IMMORTALITY
DOYLE, BRIAN
U.S. CATHOLIC, JUNE 1990. PP6-13.
