!TITLE
THE MEASURE OF MATURITY
!WORDS
The author relates the experience of feeling disturbed and distressed 
by the overwhelming needs of a deformed beggar in Madras, India. 
Speculating about what Jesus would do when confronted with such 
overwhelming human needs, he goes on to explore the idea of what it 
means for a Christian to be fully human.  When Christ comes into a 
life, He restores and heals and enables us to become fully human.  We 
have a new compassion for our fellow creatures.  Instead of measuring 
spiritual maturity by the externals of dollars given, souls saved, 
Scriptures memorized, and seminars attended, perhaps we should 
evaluate to what extent we have allowed Christ to turn our 
indifference into true compassion for others.
    These days the word love is like a dehorned bull.  It has 
strength but appears weak. Substituting words like "honor,"  
"respect," and "dignify" for the word "love" in Scripture can put the 
horns back on the bull and give us a new perspective on what it means 
to love in the way Jesus commanded us to.  Fully human Christians 
will look the pain and affliction of the world full in the face and 
look to Christ for the grace to respond as He would.  If you are not 
sure you can embrace this suffering world in that way, perhaps you 
are already on the way to doing it because it is not something you 
can do in your own strength. It is only His grace that empowers us to 
treat others as fully human.

      "The measure of maturity" by Fred Askins. Discipleship Journal, 
Jul/Aug 1990.  Pages 44-47.
!TOPICS
MINISTRY
