!TITLE
MEET THE PRESS
!WORDS
A nationally syndicated columnist declares that the anti-Christian 
bias of the media is a provable fact but that it is not the result of 
some sort of conspiracy.  Usually such prejudice in journalists has 
its roots in early life experiences that somehow turned them against 
God. Media people like to consider themselves pluralists, but a 
significant number of them grew up in the church only to reject the 
faith later. Their antagonism toward religion often reflects their 
desire to justify their liberal views. Christians themselves are 
partly to blame for the way the press misrepresents Christianity.  
Too many of those who say they believe in God live as if He didn't 
really exist.  Only 11% of Christians read the Bible daily.  How can 
a generation that is Biblically illiterate expect to have the mind of 
Christ?  Only through a deeper commitment to the Lord and to our 
families, more faithful Bible study, and more fervent prayer can we 
have the kind of spiritual power that even the secular media cannot 
ignore.
      "Meet the press" by Cal Thomas.  Christian Herald, Sep/Oct 
1990.  Pages 16-19.
