!TITLE
ADJUSTING THEOLOGY IN THE SHADOW OF AUSCHWITZ
!WORDS
Last year when a group of evangelical theologians issued a statement 
about Christians evangelizing Jews, a rabbi from the American Jewish 
Committee reacted by calling it a "blueprint for spiritual 
genocide."  In recent years many Christian leaders and scholars have 
vehemently attacked the traditional concept of salvation through 
Christ which is the basis for evangelism.  For example, one 
Protestant theologian said Jesus may be the Christ of the Church but 
He is not the Messiah promised in the Old Testament.  Another claims 
that the New Testament is basically an anti-Semitic document.  A 
third speaks of dropping the doctrine of the Resurrection in order to 
correct the Christian misconception of Judaism. These ideas are known 
as two-covenant theology. For many of the adherents of this school of 
thought, both Christians and Jews, the Holocaust is the pivotal event 
in history by which every other event must be understood, even the 
Resurrection and the Exodus.

   The evangelical rejection of two-covenant theology does not grow 
out of anti-Semitism but out of our understanding of the nature of 
God's revelation in Scripture.  If theology is the effort to discover 
unchanging truth in God's Word, then the words may have a different 
significance and a different application at certain points in 
history, but the theology itself is not changed by historical events, 
no matter how cataclysmic.  The problem is that two-covenant theology 
assumes that the whole idea of salvation is somehow off-base. 
Ironically, however, these theologians have no category for false 
religion, which was certainly an important matter to Moses and other 
Old Testament writers.  So it is two-covenant theology itself which 
is a blueprint for spiritual genocide because it will ensure the 
spiritual death of an entire group of people by withholding the 
gospel from them.
      "Adjusting theology in the shadow of Auschwitz" by Kenneth 
Myers.  Christianity Today, Oct 8, 1990.  Pages 41-43.
!TOPICS
JEWS AND CHRISTIANS
THEOLOGY, TWO-COVENANT
