!TITLE
PROMISES TO THE WORLD'S CHILDREN MUST BE KEPT
!WORDS
Leaders from 71 nations recently gathered at the United Nations for a 
World Summit for Children to consider overwhelming problems like (1) 
the fact that 14 million children under five die every year from 
malnutrition and easily preventable diseases, (2) the dramatic 
increase in the number of AIDS orphans--children whose parents have 
both died of AIDS--who may or may not have the disease themselves, 
and (3) the suffering of millions of other children because of poor 
sanitation and lack of basic education.

   The leaders set ambitious goals for improving the quality of life 
for children, but to meet their goals would cost $7.5 billion by the 
year 2000.  In order for anything significant to be accomplished in 
this area, the nations represented at the summit, especially those 
that currently allocate 50% or more of their national budget to 
military expenditures, are going to have to restructure their 
priorities.  Governments have the power to keep these promises to 
children, but the question is do they have the will?

      "Promises to the world's children must be kept." Episcopal 
Life, Nov 1990.  Page 24.
