!TITLE
EXPERIENCING THE PRESENCE OF GOD DURING TIMES OF NEED
!WORDS
An Episcopal rector describes a case study in which he interviewed a 
dozen people about their personal experiences of sensing the presence 
of God in times of trouble.  Six of them were atheists or agnostics, 
and the other six were active church members.  The Christian 
interviewees all shared vivid accounts of how God had helped them in 
their time of need.  The non- believers had similar experiences of 
escaping from difficult circumstances but attributed their 
deliverance to luck or their own skill.  However, the difference 
between the two groups was not just a matter of labels.

   The Christians who experienced the presence of God all indicated 
that it resulted in a changed outlook and an ability to cope with 
their particular challenges more successfully. Also, although members 
of both groups went through similar emotions (fear, joy, anxiety), 
the Christians found a great sense of peace based upon their belief 
in the purposefulness of their existence.  The atheists did not have 
this peace, particularly when facing death.  The writer feels 
strongly that the conviction on the part of the Christians that God 
had definitely intervened in their lives will give them an internal 
strength for facing future trials. The non-believers simply do not 
have any comparable resource.
  "Experiencing the presence of God during times of need: a case 
study" by Robert Marston.  Journal of Pastoral Care, Fall 1990. Pages 
258-264.
!TOPICS
PRESENCE, GOD'S
SUFFERING
