!TITLE
THE RISE OF THE RUDE
!WORDS
  » "How strangers treat one another in the random swirl of daily 
life says something about their society."«

   This lengthy cover story laments and analyzes the decline of 
courtesy and manners in our society.  One psychiatrist says the trend 
goes much deeper: it is actually a loss of respect for public spaces 
and for the people who occupy that space. One of the most obvious 
examples of how social interaction has degenerated is the way people 
drive nowadays.  One poll found that 38% of Southern Californians 
admitted having made an obscene gesture at another driver,and one out 
of five had run a red light in the past month.  Our culture is so 
stubbornly individualistic that there is a natural tendency to regard 
civility as effete. The way people interact with strangers in 
everyday situations reveals a great deal about the inner workings of 
society.  One philosophy professor at Catholic University fears that 
when protective barriers that seem to be inconsequential are torn 
down, core values start to crumble.  He muses, "I'm not suggesting 
that manners are morals, but there is a kind of endemic 
thoughtlessness that's really combative selfishness."

   Why is our society so rude?  Some attribute it, at least in part, 
to our being oversaturated with the media.  The break-neck pace of 
modern life is another part of it, but some say that is no excuse 
because life has always been stressful. Perhaps the lion's share of 
the blame for this rampant rudeness must be placed on the changes 
that have taken place in the American family.  Married couples with 
children made up 44% of all households in the United States in 1960.  
Just 30 years later that figure has shrunk to only 26%. The resulting 
explosion of single-parent families is compounded by the rise of 
two-income households.  Both trends mean that there's seldom anyone 
around to tell (and show) kids how to be courteous. "When Mom went to 
work, the moral compass at home lost its magnetic north."

   Even conscientious parents face a difficult struggle.  The 
hyper-individualism of the 1960s still echoes in the national psyche 
as freedom continues to degenerate into irresponsibility and 
self-worth becomes nothing more than narcissism.

      "The rise of the rude" by Tom Dunkel. Insight, Dec 2, 1991.  
Pages 4-9+.
