!TITLE
THE PASSION-DRIVEN CHURCH
!WORDS
  » "Newly planted churhces sometimes fall into the trap of trying to 
clone themselves on 'successful' churches, but clones almost never 
work."«

   The writer, a church-planter who has started four new churches, 
was able to build his first congregation on the basis of meeting 
needs.  Lots of people came to have the needs met but few shared his 
vision for the church.  Out of that experience he determined that his 
church-planting ministry should not center around the purpose of a 
church but around passions--deeply held visionary values.  He gives a 
sampling of the values that drive his current church.
   (1) It is an evangelical church on the cutting edge.  It strives 
to provide real answers to contemporary questions.  It is 
progressive, always moving ahead.  These are the kinds of values in a 
church that people can commit themselves to.  (2) Their worship 
services are designed for believers, but they are sensitive to the 
fact that outsiders will be present.  Rather than gearing everything 
around those seekers, they simply try to allow them the opportunity 
to sample a genuine time of worship. (3) As a church they rejoice in 
seeing people moving toward committed discipleship even if their 
current lifestyles don't quite fit the mold.  (4) They emphasize 
building people rather than running programs.  The kind of people 
they want to develop is not super-talented performers but ordinary 
Christians who have an impact on others wherever they are.  One 
woman, for example, a victim of sexual abuse in childhood, found that 
leading a group with people from a similar background helped her deal 
with her own pain.
   This kind of focus on values is not compatible with most 
church-growth theories, so the writer found that he had to correct 
several misconceptions in his own thinking in order to pursue them.  
He found the following principles helpful.
   (1) Even though it's tempting in starting a new work to latch on 
to anyone who shows an interest, be selective in who you recruit.  
Certain types of people will keep the church from reaching its goal.  
Among them are consumers (those who are more concerned about getting 
their own needs met than about investing in the mission of the 
church), antagonists (those who don't agree with the church's vision 
and try to undercut it), and those who, though they may like the new 
church, don't really share its values.
   (2) Don't try to emulate some other successful church. Church 
planters need to be entrepreneurs-- nonconformists, self-starters, 
innovative thinkers--who set out to do something new. Comparing 
itself with another church can wreck the new group's self-image.
   (3) Focus on values rather than on techniques or programs 
regardless of how time-tested they may be.  Values alone can give 
biblical direction to your growth.
   (4) The effective church planter is so committed to the vision of 
what God wants to do that he may appear to be insensitive to the 
needs of individuals.  He will even be willing to risk alienating a 
few people along the way in order to reach the goal.
   (5) Although consensus is highly valued in our culture, that is 
not the kind of leadership a new church needs.  Committees seldom 
generate strong values.  For that you need a point man--normally the 
pastor.  This doesn't mean that a pastor should be dictatorial.  
There is a distinction between a strong leader who sees what God is 
trying to accomplish and one who tries to manipulate or control 
others.  Leaders have to be sensitive to people, but they also have 
to lead. The writer concludes, "What has worked for me is to state my 
values, selling the vision in sermons, classes, and conversations."

      "The passion-driven church" by Paul Johnson. Leadership, Spr 
1992.  Pages 64-69.
!TOPICS
CHURCH GROWTH
VISION
VALUES, SHARED
LEADERSHIP
