!TITLE
THE TRUTH WILL SET YOU FREE
!WORDS
  » "Why did Paul, the greatest evangelist of all time, never get the 
believers together to bind the evil spirits dominating Corinth or 
Ephesus?"«

   One of the hottest topics among evangelical leaders today is 
spiritual warfare, the idea of taking the offensive against Satan by 
binding the evil spirits that control a particular geographic area.  
Some tout this as not only the key to personal prosperity and victory 
but also to world evangelization as well.
   The apostle Paul said that we wrestle against principalities and 
powers and "the rulers of the darkness of this world."  He encouraged 
believers to stand against the devil but never told us to attack 
Satan or to try to bind him.  Advocates of the "territorial spirit" 
theory usually use Dan. 10:13 to support their approach.  This verse 
explains that the "prince of the kingdom of Persia" kept the angel 
Gabriel from getting through to Daniel for three weeks.  Note, 
however, that Daniel was not praying for the conversion of Persia, 
and neither he nor Gabriel attempted to "bind" this demon, if indeed 
the prince was a demon.

   In recent years Larry Lea has been organizing what he calls 
"prayer breakthroughs" in various cities to "take captive demonic 
strongholds." Some 1,300 Los Angeles pastors have been meeting to 
wage spiritual warfare for the deliverance of their city, and similar 
groups have sprung up around the country. While their concern for the 
lost is commendable, neither their objective nor their strategy is 
scriptural.  An individual response by sinners to the gospel is what 
is necessary for salvation.  The Bible does not mention mass 
denunciation of demons by Christians. Three years ago Lea proclaimed 
that the demonic strongholds dominating the greater Los Angeles area 
would be pulled down by militant spiritual warfare.  He also led 
Christians in San Francisco to bind the demon of homosexuality, but 
there has been no decrease in the sexual perversion in that city.

   Another supporter of this movement, C. Peter Wagner, professor at 
Fuller Seminary, teaches "authoritative prayer." Rather than asking 
according to God's will, this is prayer that commands God to do 
particular things.  Christians are urged to command Satan and demons, 
too, to release a person or city.  It is only our commitment to 
Christ, our love for God, and our obedience to His Word that will 
defeat Satan in our lives. Sometimes a situation requires that a 
demon be cast out of a non-Christian, but Jesus and his disciples 
never went looking for evil spirits to do battle with (Acts 
16:16-18).  The "strongholds" we are to destroy are not demon 
fortresses but rebellious thought patterns that elevate self above 
God.  Trying to overcome sin using these unscriptural "spiritual 
warfare" techniques can be devastating.  It is, of course, easier to 
blame an evil spirit than to take responsibility for your own 
actions, but it also denies the power of the indwelling Christ.

   When Jesus was tempted by Satan, He did not rebuke him or bind 
him.  He resisted him with the Word, and we are to do the same by 
understanding, believing, and obeying that Word in the power of the 
Holy Spirit.  [See also 7710.]
      "The truth will set you free" by Dave Hunt. The Berean Call, 
May 1992.  Pages 1-3.
