!TITLE
ABANDONED BABIES
!WORDS
  » "Based on this data, we estimate that these 72 urban safety net 
hospitals will board 6,500-7,000 babies this year at a total 
unreimbursed cost of $30 million."«

   Last spring a survey found that 72 hospitals in a dozen major 
cities were caring for some 600 abandoned infants.  A few of them 
were HIV- infected, but 85% were suffering from prenatal exposure to 
alcohol, cocaine, or other drugs.  At that point, some of the babies 
had already been in the hospital for longer than three months.  Since 
each infant's care costs around $700 a day, it is estimated that the 
cost of caring for the 6,500 to 7,000 abandoned babies these 
institutions board in the course of a year may top $30 million.  The 
study was conducted by the Child Welfare League and the National 
Association of Public Hospitals.

      "Thousands of unwanted babies left at public hospitals." Pulpit 
Helps, Nov 1992.  Page 17. Main topic: CHILDREN.  See also 7775.
