!TITLE
IT'S NOT LIKE MR. MOM
!WORDS
  » "Single fathers are now one of the fastest- growing segments of 
the American population."«

   At the beginning of the 1980s only 10% of single parents were 
men.  By 1991, that percentage grew to 15% (or 1.2 million U.S. 
households).  A few are widowers (7.5%), some never married (25%), 
but the majority are divorced (66%).  Almost one- third of the single 
fathers have custody of preschool children.
   The increase in the number of single fathers can be partly 
attributed to the fact that many men today are taking a greater 
interest in childrearing and are unwilling to give up that role even 
though their marriage falls apart.  In the past the courts almost 
always awarded custody to the mother especially if the children were 
younger, but since more moms work outside the home these days, what's 
best for the child is not so clear-cut.  More children of divorce 
(88%) live with their mothers, but fathers are increasingly likely to 
ask for and gain custody.  One benefit of this trend lies in the fact 
that noncustodial mothers tend to stay involved in their children's 
lives more often than noncustodial fathers do.
   Single fathers encounter many problems ranging from the routine 
domestic chores to legal bias. They often feel isolated because they 
do not have the support system single mothers usually do. Some are 
ridiculed for choosing to take on a role traditionally reserved for 
women.

      "It's not like Mr. Mom" by Jean Seligman. Newsweek, Dec 14, 
1992.  Pages 70-73.  Topic: FATHERS, SINGLE.  See also 8317 and 8126.
!TOPICS
FATHERS, SINGLE
PARENTHOOD, SINGLE
