!TITLE
THE FIRST NOEL
!WORDS
    "While many scholars have come to reject the historical veracity 
of at least some of the details [of the Christmas narrative], many 
others have found little reason to alter traditional understanding of 
a story that, at its heart, is a call to faith in a supernatural God."

   Bible scholars have long debated whether the familiar story of 
Christ's birth should be read as history, myth, theology, or some 
combination of the three.  Thanks to the tools of archaeology and 
textual research, some new insights have emerged from this ongoing 
re-examination.  Although many researchers have rejected the 
historicity of at least some of the Christmas story's details, a 
significant number see no reason to throw out the traditional account 
since it is less a biography than an invitation to believe in a 
miracle-working God.

   The New Testament itself is virtually the only source of 
information we have concerning the birth of Christ, but many scholars 
say the Nativity material in Luke and Matthew was not part of the 
earliest Christian traditions as was the Resurrection.  These 
skeptics point out that the celebration of Christmas did not become 
popular until after 400 A.D., and that if the New Testament writers 
had been aware of such miraculous events surrounding the birth of 
their Lord, they would have referred to them thousands of times in 
their writings.  Some say the discrepancies between Luke's and 
Matthew's accounts destroy the credibility of either. Matthew records 
that Joseph and Mary took the Child to Egypt to escape Herod's wrath, 
but Luke has them returning directly to Nazareth.

   Luke's account raises other questions.  Why would a woman in 
Mary's condition choose to make the difficult 85-mile trip from 
Nazareth to Bethlehem when Joseph could have gone alone?  The obvious 
answer, some say, is that Mary knew the Old Testament prophecies 
about the Messiah being born in Bethlehem and realized that the Roman 
census decree was all part of God's plan.  Luke's description of the 
census is even more puzzling. No extrabiblical source refers to a 
universal census ordered by Caesar Augustus even though the records 
show he conducted censuses of Roman citizens in 28 B.C., 8 B.C., and 
14 A.D.  The only recorded census involving the Syrian governor 
Quirinius did not take place until 6 A.D., almost ten years after the 
death of Herod (who is a major character in Matthew's account).  Some 
scholars say the problem is not with Luke's facts but with 
mistranslations.  Others say Luke's purpose was not to fix the date 
but only to indicate how God used even the most powerful individual 
on earth as part of His plan to provide a Savior.

   The story of the Magi as told by Matthew has been questioned by 
many scholars.  Since secular history includes no record of a 
celestial phenomenon like the fabled star, they view this part of the 
narrative as allegorical.  Other experts say that an alignment of 
Jupiter (the "king" of the planets) with Mars and Saturn(associated 
with Palestine) in the constellation Pisces (the sign of epochal 
events) would have been interpreted by astrologers of that time as an 
indication that a ruler had been born. This alignment, which happens 
only once every 805 years, occurred in 6 B.C.

   Skeptics also say Herod's slaughter of infants at Bethlehem would 
have been recorded by the Jewish historian Josephus if it had really 
happened.  Defenders of Matthew's veracity counter that possibly as 
few as 10 or 12 babies were involved and that would have easily been 
overshadowed by the other atrocities Herod committed.

      "The first Noel" by Jeffrey Sheler.  U.S. News & World Report, 
Dec 21, 1992.  Pages 78-89. Topic: CHRISTMAS.  See also 8356 and 8171.
!TOPICS
CHRISTMAS
JESUS CHRIST, BIRTH OF
SCRIPTURE, ACCURACY OF
NATIVITY
LUKE, GOSPEL OF
MATTHEW, GOSPEL OF
HISTORY
SHELER, JEFFREY
US NEWS & WORLD REP, 921221 PP78-89.
CRITICISM-EVIDENCES
