!TITLE
TEN WAYS TO BE A BETTER FATHER
!WORDS
  » "It takes a lot of energy to shape the lives God has entrusted to 
us as fathers."«

   Despite the fact that much attention has been drawn to the lack of 
positive male role models for today's children, many fathers are 
trying to fulfill the responsibilities of fatherhood.  Some tips from 
an experienced father of four will offer help to Christian fathers.
   Love your wife.  Both boys and girls need to see their parents as 
a couple devoted to one another.
   Be a man of integrity.  Let your children see that you are 
consistent in your character, both in public and in private.
   Let your childrn know they are important to you. They'll evaluate 
this by how much time you spend with them and how important their 
interests are to you.
   Give them a sense of self-worth.  A dad's words of praise or 
criticism have a deep and lasting effect on children.
   Communicate as a family.  Children need the security of a united 
family.  Dads, learn to really listen to your children and their 
concerns.
   Understand your purpose.  Make it your goal to give to the world 
the gift of your children, trained and prepared for service.
   Be vulnerable.  Your children already know you're not perfect; go 
ahead and admit it.
   Use discipline to develop character, not to get rid of your 
anger.  Know the difference between being displeased with a child's 
behavior and taking action to correct and train, and hitting your 
child because his misbehavior has irritated you.
   Let children experience the consequences of their choices. 
Feeling the pain of bad decisions teaches them the relationship 
between reaping and sowing, an important life principle.
   Show tenderness.  Expressions of affection are vital.
   Life is uncertain; each opportunity might be the last chance 
fathers have to give themselves to their children.
      "10 ways to be a better father" by Crawford Loritts.  Urban 
Family, Wint 1993.  Pages 22-23. Topic: FATHERS.  See also 8488 and 
8432.
!TOPICS
