!TITLE
THE POWER OF FAMILY EMOTIONS
!WORDS
  » "Research indicates that as much as 50% of some personality 
traits may be genetically determined. Thus the same home environment 
will affect individuals differently."«

   Stress, which comes in an increasingly bewildering array of forms 
today, often damages family relationships.  A family's physical and 
emotional resources can be depleted when a variety of stress factors 
stack up.  The family has to fight against these overwhelming 
circumstances with their current coping strategies or learn new ones, 
perhaps by requesting help from other people.

   What often happens is that a family under stress will try to gain 
short-term release from the tension through vacations, physical 
exercise, or denial that things are as bad as they seem. Yet these 
inadequate solutions only add to the problem because the root cause 
is being ignored. Another frequent result is that people start 
projecting their own inadequacies on to someone else, e.g., a child 
with a serious health problem. The longer these maladaptive coping 
methods are used, the more difficult it becomes for the family to 
pull out of the cycle of anxiety and depression.

   Anxiety may well be the most common psychiatric malady in the 
United States.  Some 65% of all new prescriptions physicians write 
are for anxiety. As many as 4% of the population suffers from anxiety 
disorder, with 2% experiencing panic attacks.

   Depression ranks in the top ten most common diagnoses made by 
primary care doctors, and studies show that it is not only becoming 
more widespread but increasingly strikes younger individuals.  This 
certainly has an adverse effect on families. Research has shown a 
definite biological factor in depression. Some people are genetically 
predisposed to become depressed. The good news is that depression is 
fairly easy to treat once it is recognized.  Anyone who suspects 
depression in himself or a family member should consult a doctor and 
feel no sense of shame about doing so.

   Other personality traits are significantly determined by genetic 
factors, too.  That's why siblings reared in the same home 
environment often turn out to be drastically different in terms of 
personality type.  Every temperament has its strengths, however, and 
it is essential that parents accept their children and help them 
overcome the negative aspects of the personality type they have 
inherited.

      "The power of family emotions" by Sharon Sneed   and David 
Sneed.  Today's Better Life, Spr 1993.  Pages 42-45+.  Topic: STRESS, 
FAMILY.  See also 8529 and 8075.
!TOPICS
STRESS, FAMILY
FAMILY BREAKDOWN
DEPRESSION
ANXIETY
COPING STRATEGIES
GENETICS
PERSONALITY TYPES
SNEED, DAVID
SNEED  , SHARON
TODAY'S BETTER LIFE, SPR 1993. PP42-45+.
