!TITLE
TIME WITH GOD
!WORDS
  » "If you desire a heart filled with devotion for Christ, spend 
time each day in close communion with Him, and let His fire set your 
heart aflame."«

   It's hard to find a Christian who thinks spending time alone with 
God is unimportant, but very few actually do it.  Dawson Trotman once 
asked a group of missionary trainees how many of them had a daily 
quiet time.  Not one hand was raised. These were not just average 
Christians but the godliest men and women of the church, willing to 
go overseas to spread the gospel.  Yet even they did not seem to take 
this simple practice seriously.

   Christians need to understand the tremendous benefits of daily 
time alone with God.
   Stress relief.  The mounting pressures of work and home 
responsibilities can lead to explosions if you don't have a safety 
valve.  Casting your cares on the Lord (1 Pet 5:7) can provide that 
release.  The problems are still there, but you don't have to bear 
the burden of them.  Speaking of some problems he faced in his 
ministry, Bill Bright once said, "I have learned that either I carry 
them or Jesus does, but we both can't do it. And so I have cast them 
on Him."

   Devotion enhancement.  A daily time with God will fan the flame 
of your devotion to Christ. The two depressed disciples on the road 
to Emmaus experienced the burning of their hearts while Jesus was 
with them.  You can, too.

   Burnout prevention.  Burnout doesn't result from overwork but 
from getting too busy to have time with the Lord. Pretty soon you're 
functioning out of the energy of the flesh rather than the power of 
the Spirit.  By His own example, Jesus showed us how it is possible 
to have the right priorities in the midst of a very busy life.

   Practical tips:  If you think you're too busy to have a quiet 
time, make regular appointments with God as you would with a doctor.  
Write them down and keep them.  Be ready for that time, which may 
mean making some preparations the night before in order to have an 
unhurried time the next morning.  Don't focus on establishing a 
habit; just remember who you're meeting with.

      "Time with God" by Leroy Eims.  Today's Better Life, Sum 1993.  
Pages 76-79.  Topic: QUIET TIME.  See also 8635 and 8522.
!TOPICS
QUIET TIME
DEVOTIONS, PERSONAL
INTIMACY WITH GOD
