!TITLE
CHILDREN RAISED...
!WORDS
  » "The groups most likely to retain the religious upbringing of 
their youth were Catholics and conservative Protestants."«

   A sociological study reported in the Review of Religious Research 
has confirmed the ancient proverb:  "Train up a child in the way he 
should go and, when he is old, he will not depart from it" (Prov. 
22:6).
   A poll of social science students at two state universities in the 
mid1980s found that young adults were more likely to continue to 
follow their early religious training if they were church attenders 
at age 10 and did not experience doubts until their later teens.  
Beliefs were more persistent for those who attended church more 
regularly and for whom doubts came later.

   Children raised in mainline Protestant denominations were more 
likely to drop out of religion as teens than were conservative 
Protestants and Catholics.  Of the college students who had dropped 
out, 40% said they did so because of the hypocrisy, racism, and 
dishonesty they saw in the church. Many also felt that religion had 
no ability to improve a person's life, yet those who had abandoned 
their childhood faith were more likely to be dissatisfied with life 
and have lower self-esteem than their more religious peers.

      "Children raised...."  National & International Religion 
Report, May 31, 1993.  Page 3.  Topic: TRAINING CHILDREN.  See also 
8711 and 8548.
!TOPICS
TRAINING CHILDREN
