!TITLE
HOW ABOUT A SWIFT KICK?
!WORDS
  » "It is difficult to say to say what harmful effects have followed 
[our] efforts to talk ourselves out of having a moral sense."   
--James Wilson«

   Geoffrey Canada's unconventional approach to moral education is a 
good swift karate kick in the pants.   Geoff is president of the 
Rheedlen Centers for Children and Families in Harlem.  In exchange 
for consummate instruction in martial arts skills, Geoff expects 
something unusual in return--virtue.  When he doesn't get it, 
retribution is swift.

   Student-cum-instructor Alex Echevarria recalls the time when two 
of Canada's young disciples were caught dealing drugs. "Geoff went to 
their houses, stripped them of their belts, and, in front of the rest 
of us, cut the belts in two with scissors."

   Why is Canada's approach so controversial? Sociologist James 
Wilson, author of The Moral Sense, would say it's because so many 
seeds of amorality were sown in the 1960s that society couldn't bring 
itself to use words like "right" and "wrong." In the poorest 
neighborhoods, laws made it increasingly difficult to screen housing 
project tenants, and police, seen as an "occupying force," were 
removed from inner-city streets. Welfare rolls soared, and, in the 
name of freedom, a popular culture of intemperance appeared.

   A recent census report documenting the skyrocketing rate of 
out-of-wedlock births was greeted with deafening silence from public 
officials, including a President who ran on a campaign of "personal 
responsibility."  At the risk of demonstrating the "stiff, humorless, 
unAmerican propriety that gave morality a bad name," perhaps it's 
time to give those who behave irresponsibly a good swift kick.

      "How about a swift kick?" by Joe Klein. Newsweek, Jul 26, 
1993.  Page 30.  Topic: VIRTUE. See also 8795 and 7895.
!TOPICS
VIRTUE
MORALS
