!TITLE
CAMBRIDGE, ENGLAND, IS SEEING...
!WORDS
  » "Cambridge is an unlikely place for a spiritual rebirth, since 
the city is dominated by a great secular university and high-tech 
economics."«

   Britain has become increasingly secular in recent years, and 
church attendance has dwindled, but renewal seems to be sprouting in 
a most unlikely place--Cambridge.  Though heavily influenced by the 
presence of a large secular university and high-tech business 
concerns, there are a dozen or more flourishing evangelical and 
charismatic congregations in the city.  Churches like St. Andrew's 
Street Baptist and Holy Trinity(Anglican) attract thousands of 
college students as well as townspeople (most from a high-church 
background).

   One observer attributes the effectiveness of these churches to 
four factors.  (1) In contrast to the liberal clergy who often seem 
more concerned about politics than spirituality, the pastors of these 
churches concentrate on preaching expositorily through entire books 
of Scripture. (2) Programs and services are informal but well- 
organized.  The fact that they are not liturgical appeals to younger 
people.  (3) Parishioners and attenders are given many opportunities 
to serve-- in the church and in the community.  One of the 
congregations, for example, operates a restaurant, homeless shelter, 
job center, and bookstore. Another has an extensive food ministry.  
(4) They are reaching out to students and the unchurched. Some of the 
churches have started new churches in outlying areas.

      "Cambridge, England, is seeing...." National & International 
Religion Report, Aug 9, 1993. Page 1.  Topic: RENEWAL, CHURCH.  See 
also 8781.
!TOPICS
RENEWAL, CHURCH
