!TITLE
PULLING WEEDS FROM YOUR FIELD OF DREAMS
!WORDS
  » "Hedonism works its way into the fabric of my visions like 
foxtails into socks."«

   Vision is an asset to any pastor.  It can become a liability, 
however, if it is not tended carefully, and good tending means being 
alert to toxic weeds.
   The Dream Weed.  Healthy daydreaming that allows us to imagine the 
possible can turn destructive if it causes us to long for the 
impossible--multiple Ph.D.'s, three secretaries to guard the pastor 
from the persnickety parishioner. Such dreams grow out of our 
frustration, our anger, and our self-pity.
   How do we pull up these dangerous dream weeds? Begin with 
confession, calling your false vision what it is and telling God 
about it.  Then repent by praying for the right things--for the 
people in your congregation, for the fruit of the Spirit, etc.
   Dream weeds cannot tolerate reality, so a good dose of reality is 
also an effective antidote. Call that persnickety parishioner.  Sweep 
the church sidewalk.  In such common ways we recommit ourselves to 
caring for our church and its people.
   The Greed Weed.  Desiring one's church to prosper and grow is a 
good thing--until, coupled with that earnest prayer, is a vision of a 
new car, a nicer flyrod, a bigger salary.
   Greed is impatient, so the best weapon against it is patience.  
Greed wants everything now.  By delaying gratification, we choke the 
weeds of greed and make room for the Spirit's fruit to grow.
   The Hero Weed.  Too often, our own faces figure prominently in our 
dreams.  We see ourselves heroically restoring a dying church to 
prominence in the community, or saving a troubled marriage through 
brilliant counseling.
   Perhaps the best way to extract our ego from our vision is through 
private prayer.  Instead of making ourselves highly visible and 
vocal, we can retreat into the anonymity of private prayer.  We will 
still see our dreams come true, but God will get the credit instead 
of our egos.
   Pastors need a vision in order to persevere. So dream on--just 
remember to check for life-choking weeds now and then.
 @Z:E

      "Pulling weeds from your field of dreams" by David Hansen. 
Leadership, Sum 1994 (Vol 15, No 3). Pages 73-77. Topic: VISION. See 
also 9477 and 8364.
!TOPICS
VISION
PASTORING
DREAMS
GREED
REALISM
HANSEN, DAVID
LEADERSHIP, SUM 1994. PP73-77.
