!TITLE
MARATHON LEADERS
!WORDS
  » "Those who have trained themselves in dogged pursuit of their 
assignment reach it."«

   What is the most important trait for a pastor wanting to lead a 
growing church?  Perseverance.
   The New Testament word hypomeno is best translated "patiently 
enduring" or "overcoming difficulties."  This unglamorous definition 
may disappoint the leader hoping to build a successful church with 
his skills, charisma, or intelligence. Nevertheless, those who 
"doggedly pursue what God has shown them" are more likely to reach 
their pastoral goals than those who rely on natural abilities.
   Perseverance is characterized by three elements:  resilience, 
learned optimism, and opportunism.
   Resilience is the ability to bounce back. Where does it come 
from?  It comes from charged batteries, from a well-guarded emotional 
and physical reserve, and from the ability to laugh at oneself.  It 
also comes from a good dose of realism that expects obstacles.
   The person with learned optimism has "an eye for what is going 
right."  Those who focus on failures and problems will not be able to 
hang in there.  Those who make a habit of thanking God for the things 
that are going well will approach each day with a renewed 
perspective.  One pastor suggested, "If you thank God 150 times a day 
before you hit the office, God will do great things."  Build times of 
prayer and praise into your daily schedule to balance all the 
trouble- shooting meetings.
   Opportunism enables the pastor to see opportunities in the midst 
of problems.  However pressing the problems, take time to consider 
new ideas.  "A dose of renewed vision resolves more issues than a 
church vote."
   In summary, Christian leadership is not for sprinters. Rather, it 
is for plodders, for marathoners, who can keep moving forward toward 
a dream.
 @Z:E

      "Marathon leaders" by Doug Murren. Ministries Today, Jul/Aug 
1994 (Vol 12, No 4). Pages 20-21. Topic: PASTORING. See also 9476 and 
8424.
!TOPICS
PASTORS, EFFECTIVE
PERSEVERANCE
DETERMINATION
VISION
OPTIMISM
MURREN, DOUG
MINISTRIES TODAY, 9407-. PP20-21.
