!TITLE
COUNTERING INDIFFERENCE
!WORDS
  » "The media rarely pay attention to Angola, where death from 
malnutrition is routine and war is constant."«

   Countries in Africa receive $60 billion in aid from the 
industrialized world each year, but since one-third of those 
countries (16 of them) are at war, the same nations that send aid 
make profits of $125 billion annually on the weapons they sell in 
Africa.  Worse yet, the industrialized nations seem totally 
indifferent to what is going on in Africa.
   Angola, rarely mentioned by the media, is a prime example. Death 
from malnutrition is commonplace there, and civil war has been raging 
ever since Portugal withdrew as a colonial power in 1975.
   The United States, as the world's only superpower, has an 
obligation to deal with situations like this.  If we would devote the 
same sort of energy and motivation to them as we did to Operation 
Desert Storm, many world problems would be solvable. However, current 
U.S. foreign policy is driven by domestic politics rather than a 
coherent moral vision concerning long-range humanitarian needs.  In 
the past, the United States used African countries as pawns in the 
cold war, but now that the Soviet Union is no longer an influence in 
the region, U.S. policy ignores Africa except when the fights and 
famines get bad enough to attract media attention.
   Even though Angola is a potentially rich nation, world 
indifference has left it standing today on the brink of mass 
starvation.  The ongoing civil war is between the elected government 
of President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.  
For years the United States backed Savimbi while Dos Santos had the 
support of the Soviets.  Both sides have tapped other sources of 
funds in recent years in order to continue the conflict.  Meanwhile, 
an estimated three million of Angola's 11 million people need 
emergency food assistance.
 
      "Countering indifference" by James Wall. Christian Century, Jul 
13, 1994 (Vol 111, No 21). Pages 667-668.  Topic: AFRICA, FAMINE IN.  
See also 8984.
!TOPICS
AFRICA, FAMINE IN
WAR, CIVIL
FOREIGN AID
