!TITLE
MORAL ABSOLUTES RETURNING
!WORDS
    » "Republicans outdistance Democrats and independents in their 
willingness to accept moral absolutes."«

   The results of a recent Gallup Poll might surprise you.  The 
question: "Do you believe in moral absolutes--that is, that some 
things are right or wrong regardless of the situation?"  The answer: 
A surprising "yes" from 68% of those polled.

   Just four years ago, in 1991, seven Americans in ten said they 
agreed that "there are few moral absolutes: what is right or wrong 
usually varies from situation to situation."  This more recent poll, 
conducted during September 1994, shows a remarkable reversal.

   Not surprisingly, those who consider religion an important part of 
their lives are more likely to believe in moral absolutes than those 
who aren't very "religious" (74% versus 58%). Willingness to accept 
moral absolutes also is more predominant among Republicans (74%) than 
Democrats(66%) or Independents (64%).

   Though relativism is usually associated with universities, it is 
noteworthy that "acceptance of moral absolutes now is more widespread 
among those who are college educated than among those whose schooling 
ended with high school graduation or earlier."

   More men believe in moral absolutes than women(73% versus 63%). 
The difference between ages is not as great as might be expected, 
with 69% of 18- 34 year-olds expressing a belief in moral absolutes 
as opposed to 72% of those age 65 and older.

  "Moral absolutes returning" by George H. Gallup, Jr.  Colorado 
Springs Gazette Telegraph, Dec 29, 1994.  Page A1.  Topic: MORAL 
ABSOLUTES.  See also 9972 and 9524F.
!TOPICS
ABSOLUTES
RELATIVISM
MORALS
ETHICS
VALUES, MORAL
BEZILLA, ROBERT
GALLUP, GEORGE
GAZETTE TELEGRAPH, 941229. P A1.
!SCRIPTURES
2 TIMOTHY 3:15
PSALMS 119:9
MATTHEW 10:31
HEBREWS 13:8
PSALMS 90:2
PSALMS 102:27
PSALMS 103:17
MALACHI 3:6
HEBREWS 1:12
