!TITLE
DOES GOD SUFFER WITH US?
!WORDS
    » "People who severely suffer are not helped by the assurance 
that all is going well."«

   In a previous issue of Pastoral Psychology (see 8363), Michael 
Cavanagh proposed that some conceptions of God are psychospiritually 
helpful, and others unhelpful.  Least helpful are the views of God as 
vengeful, needy, as a caretaker, and as a tutor.  Marcel Sarot of 
Utrecht University, The Netherlands, further develops the theological 
distinction between adequate and inadequate conceptions of God.

   The task is challenging because it's difficult to diagnose the 
concept of God underlying a problem, and because the minister must 
have the theological discernment of what are satisfactory and 
unsatisfactory concepts.  Concerning compassion, at issue is whether 
the helpful view of God is as a fellow-sufferer or as an impassible 
non-sufferer.

   God as a co-sufferer is validated by the belief that only one who 
really suffers is able to identify with and enter into another's 
pain, thereby offering comfort and hope.  On the other hand, some 
argue that God is able to give comfort because He Himself is not 
suffering as we are, and He offers hope that all will be well in the 
long run.

   Sarot's conclusion is that both concepts can be beneficial, 
depending on the degree of pain and suffering involved.  God as 
impassible and non- suffering is demonstrated by the parent who is 
able to comfort and sympathize with a child's relatively minor 
sufferings because he is not experiencing the same agony the child 
is.  For serious griefs, however, it is more comforting to think of 
God as entering into our suffering with us, though not "participating 
in and upset by each discomfort."  Empirical research is beginning to 
confirm this theological position.

  "Pastoral counseling and the compassionate God" by Marcel Sarot.  
Pastoral Psychology, Jan 1995(Vol 43, No 3).  Pages 185-190.  Topic: 
GOD, CONCEPT OF.  See also 10046 and 8363.
!TOPICS
GOD, CONCEPT OF
PASTORAL COUNSELING
COMPASSION
SUFFERING
GOD, ATTRIBUTES OF
COMFORT
AFFLICTION
PAIN
SAROT, MARCEL
PASTORAL PSYCH, 9501. PP185-190.
