!TITLE
FATHERS, INSTRUCT YOUR CHILDREN
!WORDS
    » "The practice of catechism is the Christian equivalent of 
looking at the box top of a jigsaw puzzle before one starts to put 
all of those hundreds of little pieces together."     As the 
Christian men's movement focuses a lot of attention on the role of 
men in the home, fathers would do well to consider the wisdom of 
earlier generations regarding this vital area and reestablish the 
practice of catechism, which simply means instruction in the basic 
doctrines of the faith.
   Catechism does not replace the Bible but rather helps children 
(and adults) see the bigger picture.  The theological categories 
learned through catechism make the details of the Scriptures more 
understandable.  Protestants have always believed that creeds, 
confessions, and catechisms are only authoritative to the extent that 
they accurately restate the teachings of Scripture, but as summary 
statements they can serve as a springboard to more effective Bible 
study.
   A cult always begins with a charismatic leader convincing his 
followers that he had found something in Scripture that everybody 
else(especially the creeds, confessions, and catechisms) has missed.  
So learning a catechism not only alleviates biblical illiteracy but 
can help safeguard young people from being taken in by the false 
teachings of a cult.
   Protestant catechisms typically use a question- answer format, as 
in the well-known beginning of the Westminster Shorter Catechism of 
1648:  "What is the chief end of man?  Man's chief end is to glorify 
God and to enjoy Him forever."
   One way for fathers to follow the scriptural injunctions to 
instruct their children about God would be to use a catechism.  In 
addition, the pastor and elders of the church as well as the Sunday 
school program should reinforce this home teaching.  Parents should 
not, however, presume that the church will provide catechetical 
instruction in place of their doing it at home.
   One by-product of teaching one's children in this way is that the 
parents learn the material, too.  Many who learned the catechism as 
children have testified how later in life the memorized questions and 
answers helped them when faced with situations of doubt or temptation.
  "Fathers, instruct your children" by Kim Riddlebarger.  Modern 
Reformation, Mar/Apr 1995. Pages 18-21.  Topic: FATHERS.  See also 
10405.
!TOPICS
CHILDREN, TEACHING
FATHERS
FAMILY LIFE
CATECHISM
BIBLICAL ILLITERACY
CULTS
HERESIES
RIDDLEBARGER, KIM
MODERN REFORMATION, 9503-. PP18-21.
