!TITLE
MORALITY'S NEW THEATRE
!WORDS
    » "It's less risky to raise personal ethical questions with 
strangers."«

    "There is a great yearning in our culture for guidance on moral 
issues," says Dr. William Vitek, a philosophy professor at Clarkson 
University in New York.  Those issues might range from whether to buy 
your child a toy gun to whether abortion is moral.  Just as people 
perceive today's issues as being more complex than in past 
generations, so they are seeking guidance through a means that 
previous generations did not have available: online communication.

    "Many people won't confide in a member of the clergy because 
they're not confident that the clergy would understand the issue," 
admits Donald Jones, professor of social ethics at Drew University.  
People also hesitate to discuss some ethical issues with friends.  By 
going online, people have the advantage of anonymity and unbiased 
opinions.  Granted, there will always be those who will "speak beyond 
their knowledge," but in most forums "you are dealing with real 
people who have a common base of experience," says Alan Kaplan, a 
private investigator who interacts with other small-business owners 
via his computer.

  "Morality's new theatre" by Jane Bahls. CompuServe Magazine, Aug 
1995 (Vol 14, No 8). Pages 45-47.  Topic: ETHICS.  See also 10549, 
10197, and 10028.
!TOPICS
ETHICS
COMPUTERS
TECHNOLOGY
MORALS
CYBERSPACE
BAHLS, JANE
COMPUSERVE MAGAZINE, 9508. PP45-47.
!SCRIPTURES
ROMANS 12:11
PROVERBS 22:29
ECCLESIASTES 5:3
ECCLESIASTES 8:16
