!TITLE
CULTURE NOTES
!WORDS
    »"Merrimack's policy may safeguard not only  the moral tone of 
the classroom, but its  intellectual tone as well."« 

   A school board in New Hampshire has instituted  a policy that 
forbids teachers to present  homosexuality as an acceptable 
lifestyle.  Some  teachers and parents are claiming censorship  
because this hamstrings their teaching of Moby  Dick, for example. 

   In fact, the new rule prevents a misreading of  some classics.  
While it's true that there are  only men aboard the Pequod and 
Ishmael shares a  bunk with another man, Melville's masterpiece is  
not about homosexuality. 

   High school teachers who think they can't teach  the classics 
without bringing up homosexuality  prove that the "Queer Theory," 
which reads all  literature in terms of homosexuality, has  
percolated down from the universities to the high schools. 

 "Culture notes" by Gene Veith.  World, Mar 23,  1996 (Vol 11, No 
1).  Page 22.  Topic: SCHOOLS,  PUBLIC.  See also 11151.
!TOPICS
