!TITLE
FORGET LINCOLN, WHAT ABOUT ME?
!WORDS
    » "The search for the good has yielded to the search for rights."«

   Once upon a time in America, men of stature recognized that 
democracy was dependent on "the virtue, character, and moral input of 
its citizens."  Today, the type of laws our founding fathers framed 
would be denounced as "attempts to legislate morality."

   This phenomenon is explored in Harvard professor Michael Sandel's 
book Democracy's Discontent.  Sandel says America has become a 
"procedural republic," in which government must remain neutral toward 
its citizens' moral and religious views. Moral issues are 
"bracketed," that is, excluded from debate.  In their place, we are 
allowed to speak of individual rights, autonomy, and choice--but not 
morals or virtue.

   This has led to conclusions that would astound political leaders 
as recently as 40 years ago-- that one form of family cannot be 
esteemed more highly than another, for example, or that one must not 
judge the morality of welfare recipients.

   The proponents of this procedural republic would find themselves 
in a dilemma, however, if they were thrust into the Lincoln-Douglas 
slavery debates (which bear striking resemblance to today's abortion 
debates).  Douglas was pro- choice, declaring that the new 
territories should be allowed to decide for themselves whether to 
permit slavery.  Lincoln insisted that "policy should express moral 
judgment, not avoid it," and since he was utterly convinced of the 
immorality of slavery, he was "anti-choice" in the debate. What would 
today's liberals do?  They'd want to side with Lincoln, but to do so 
would violate their own "strictures against appeals to comprehensive 
moral ideals."

   A rights-based outlook severely restricts the open debate that is 
vital to a healthy democracy. Thankfully, there are a few rays of 
hope.  After many years of rights-talk about divorce, for example, 
people are finally looking at it in terms of moral and social 
consequences--especially for children.  May it be one step of many 
toward restoring a balanced democracy, one that Lincoln would 
recognize.

  "Forget Lincoln, what about me?" by John Leo. U.S. News & World 
Report, Apr 29, 1996 (Vol 120, No 7).  Page 23.  Topic: MORALS.  See 
also 11303, 10738, 10610, 10553, and 10201.
!TOPICS
MORALS
PLURALISM
RIGHTS, HUMAN
VIRTUE
DEMOCRACY
LEO, JOHN
US NEWS & WORLD REP, 960429. P23.
!SCRIPTURES
