!TITLE
HOW TO RAISE MORAL (AND JEWISH) CHILDREN
!WORDS
    » "At the heart and soul of Jewish moral values is the duty to 
remember our obligation to others."«

   The Jewish faith puts the onus of moral training where it 
belongs--on the parent.  "The Hebrew word for parents is horim, which 
means to guide."  Parents are expected to pass on to their children 
the values of Jewish tradition.
   Parents exercise a profound influence on their children--for good 
or for ill.  "Children watch you intently.  Your choices and deeds 
build ethical memories within them."  These memories later guide a 
child when he must decide what to do in a given situation.
   Parents who say one thing and do another leave their children 
vulnerable, without "the courage or the incentive to make moral 
choices later on in life," says psychologist Gene Ridberg.
   Jewish tradition is rich in object lessons for proper behavior.  
For example, the Shabbat challah loaves are covered.  Why?  To save 
them the embarrassment of being blessed last, after the Shabbat 
wine.  Compassion for a loaf of bread is expected to translate into a 
concern for the feelings of others.  Parents should be alert to 
teachable moments in which to instill moral values in their children.
   Judaism places great emphasis on mitzvot or good deeds.  This 
reinforces in the consciences of Jewish children the importance of 
compassion. Children are often taught charity at an early age. In one 
family, after a surplus of toys and games were received at a birthday 
party, the celebrant wrapped the duplicates and took them to a 
shelter. This child had learned well how to consider the needs of 
others and share generously.
   Great value is also placed on zeman kevua, or doing good deeds at 
the right time.  There is a set time to observe Shabbat, to pay a 
call on the bereaved, to visit the sick, or to pray.  When a family 
practices good deeds together at set times, children acquire a sense 
of responsibility.
   Through parental example and the teaching of traditions rich in 
object lessons, parents can empower their children to live 
compassionately and confidently.

  "How to raise moral (and Jewish) children" by Helen Belitsky.  
Jewish Family & Life, Spr 1996. Pages 28-30.  Topic: CHILDREN, 
TRAINING.  See also 11335, 11186, 10851, 10477, and 10405.
!TOPICS
CHILDREN, TRAINING
PARENTING
FAMILY LIFE
MORALS
JEWISH TRADITIONS
HOME LIFE
BELITSKY, HELEN
JEWISH FAMILY & LIFE, SPR 1996. PP28-30.
!SCRIPTURES
DEUTERONOMY 4:9
DEUTERONOMY 31:13
