!TITLE
FATHERHOOD ABORTED
!WORDS
    »"It wasn't a problem that was aborted; it was my child."   
--Anonymous father

   Warren Williams can tell you how abortion affects the fathers 
involved.  He has counseled 65 postabortive fathers and found them 
deeply troubled by guilt, fear of God's wrath, and sexual 
dysfunction.  It doesn't help that encouraging or allowing an 
abortion is one of those sins that you just can't talk about in 
church.  In some cases, the church's attitude is what drove an 
unmarried couple to seek an abortion in the first place.
   The church expresses amazement at figures that show abortion to be 
commonplace in the Christian community.  Yet this same church has 
failed to help its young people understand their sexuality and 
develop biblical convictions about it.
   So Christians find themselves among the growing number of men 
whose entire masculine identity is threatened by postabortion 
syndrome.  These men often struggle with "fear of women and an 
inability to bond emotionally."  They may exhibit unusual rage, 
sometimes physical violence. Compliance in an abortion also tends to 
leave a man with an inability to keep commitments-- including those 
at work.
   The father of an aborted child must begin the path to healing by 
taking responsibility for what has happened.  Next, he must allow 
himself to grieve over the child and over his sin.  With the help of 
a mature believer, he should study the Scriptures relating to God's 
mercy, and seek forgiveness. The next step is education about 
biblical manliness.  He needs to grasp the "virtues of commitment, 
sacrifice, provision, protection, and unselfish intimacy," and then 
practice these virtues in his relationships.
   Churches can help with each of these steps, but first they must 
end the reign of ignorance and secrecy, and speak openly about sexual 
sin and Christ's solution.  The pastor needs to preach clearly on 
fornication, adultery, and abortion-- and on repentance and healing 
through Christ. Youth programs and adult Bible studies can teach men 
about sexual purity and help them withstand cultural pressures.  
Church leaders can seek the help of local crisis pregnancy centers, 
who are often equipped to help men with postabortion syndrome.
 "Fatherhood aborted" by Guy Condon.  Christianity Today, Dec 9, 1996 
(Vol 40, No 14).  Pages 36-39. Topic: ABORTION.  See also 11808, 
11443, 11116, and 11106.
