!TITLE
FOUR BIG FAT LIES ABOUT KIDS
!WORDS
    »"I've seen a steady, clomping parade of statements describing 
young people [negatively]-- many of them lies masquerading as truth."«

   Generation X and the millennial generation which follows have 
often been portrayed negatively in Christian media.  Yet those 
concerned with the young people should ask an important question 
about these portrayals:  Are they accurate?  Four of the most 
commonly heard complaints may not be accurate.
   Today's kids are unable to discern right from wrong.  Josh 
McDowell's 1995 book Right From Wrong reinforced this popular 
understanding.  McDowell says, "Most of our youth lack the most basic 
moral perspectives that previous generations took for granted."  
While we may want to believe that previous generations had stronger 
moral fiber, what did they actually do when faced with similar 
struggles and temptations?  "Young people [of previous generations] 
struggled with moral boundaries, but those struggles remained largely 
private because there was no mass media to break down private 
boundaries and force them onto a public platform."

   Today's kids have short attention spans. Modern teen thinking 
processes are different than any previous generation because these 
teens process massive amounts of information.  Instead of lamenting 
so-called short attention spans, the ability of today's kids have to 
process massive amounts of information should be seen as an asset, 
not a liability.  "They're not bored because they're shallow; they're 
bored because their minds are voracious, fast-paced info eaters."

   Today's kids are not willing to commit.  While church attendance 
in overall is stagnant, teenagers are going to church in greater 
numbers. They are not going because parents are making them, but 
because they want to go.  Teens are hungry for truth and meaning, and 
are willing to take initiative to find it.  They aren't unwilling to 
commit, but they are cautious.  More than any other generation, 
they've faced "devastating betrayals" from families broken by divorce.

   Today's kids are lazy.  The slacker label is one which has stuck 
tenaciously, but statistics documenting teen volunteer involvement 
reveal a different picture.  In 1996, 13.3 million teenagers 
volunteered a total of 2.4 billion hours. Movements such as See You 
at the Pole, Teen Mania, True Love Waits, Urbana 96, Group Workcamps 
and World Vision's 30-Hour Famine challenging youth to live lives of 
purity, service, commitment, and integrity have had tremendous 
success.

 "Four big fat lies about kids" by Rick Lawrence. Group, May/Jun 1997 
(Vol 23, No 4).  Pages 18-19. Topic: BABY BUSTERS.  See also 12313, 
12310, 11990, and 11756.
!TOPICS
BABY BUSTERS
GENERATION X
YOUTH MINISTRY
TEENAGERS
MORALS
VALUES, CHRISTIAN
LAZINESS
LAWRENCE, RICK
GROUP, 9705-. PP18-19.
