!TITLE
A NO-FAULT HOLOCAUST
!WORDS
    »"Overdosing on nonjudgmentalism is a growing problem in the 
schools."«

   Teaching multiculturalism and "values clarification"--contemporary 
educational approaches that place emphasis on developing 
nonjudgmental attitudes--may be contributing to an inability among 
today's students to express moral reservations or objections to such 
horrors as human sacrifice, ethnic cleansing, and slavery. Those who 
have taught for many years are observing a definite shift in student 
views on moral issues.

   One philosophy instructor finds from 10% to 20% of his college 
students unable to say that what the Nazis did in World War II was 
morally wrong. Instead, students couch their disapproval of mass 
killings in terms of their personal preferences. Another instructor 
finds students sympathetic to the perceived need for a ritual killing 
in Shirley Jackson's short story "The Lottery" and hesitant to 
condemn a long-standing tradition that earlier generations of 
students have found morally reprehensible.

   This lack of judgmentalism is not consistent in all applications.  
Whereas human sacrifice is a debatable topic, issues such as smoking, 
environmentalism, and animal rights evoke a definite moral stand.  
Instructors are finding that a growing number of students who have an 
inability to condemn such events as the Holocaust readily assert that 
treating humans as superior to dogs and rodents is immoral.  A 
commitment to moral relativism, or "absolutophobia," is inhibiting 
many students from saying that some behavior is just plain wrong.

 "A no-fault Holocaust" by John Leo.  U.S. News & World Report, Jul 
21, 1997 (Vol 123, No 3).  Page 14.  Topic:  VALUES, MORAL.  See also 
de289, 12495, and 12420.
!TOPICS
VALUES, MORAL
MORALS
ETHICS
EDUCATION
MULTICULTURALISM
STUDENTS, COLLEGE
RELATIVISM
POSTMODERNISM
LEO, JOHN
US NEWS & WORLD REP, 970721. P14.
!SCRIPTURES
ROMANS 12:11
